column1: As of 31 August 2022, how many confirmed cases of monkeypox will be reported in countries where the disease is not endemic, according to Global Health?
column5: ['Fewer than 1,000', 'Between 1,000 and 5,000, inclusive', 'More than 5,000 but fewer than 25,000', 'Between 25,000 and 100,000, inclusive', 'More than 100,000 but fewer than 250,000', '250,000 or more']
column6: ['Technology', 'Society', 'Health']
All in

Global Health is reporting 47,652 confirmed cases at 8/26/22. The ten endemic countries are reporting 443 confirmed cases, leaving 47,209 cases in non-endemic countries. 92 non-endemic countries are reporting cases, 93 non-endemic countries are non reporting cases. 83 countries are reporting less than 1,000 cases, 50 are in single digits. The nine countries with 1,000 or more cases account for 41,571 cases.
The chance it will top 100k now is vanishingly low.
US appears to have peaked. 16.5k now. 7-day average is 437 => that would get us a bit over 31k at the
Calling it—insufficient time for big surprises to unfold.
News

According to Our World in Data, the current estimate (as of 08/14/2022) is 35 032 cases. In the last 15 days, the number of cases has increased by ~15,000 cases. If the exponential curve continues, we should expect the total number to surpass more than 50 000 cases in the next fifteen days. Also, if other countries increase their testing capacity in the next fifteen days, we should expect to see a global increase in cases. ...beyond what we can expect with the current growth.
There is some chance that continued exponential growth in the US can push the global number of cases over 100k by August 31st.
This goes against my rule of never-100%-unless-the-crowd-is-already-there, but here goes
The uncertainty here is about if and when the US growth rate slows.
Global doubling period is currently 18 days and steadily lengthening. There are only 26 days left till the end of this challenge. I estimate the final figure will be between around 60k.
Even an unlikely mutation at this point that made monkeypox much more contagious would have a difficult time pushing confirmed cases to 100,000 by the end of the month.

Leaving a very small sliver of probability on bin #5, to account for a scenario where there is a sudden, near-term and widespread expansion in the number of cases within demographics beyond the more closely monitored MSM patient group.
It's done.
Dialed in.
With case dump today I think <25k is now out of the question
Reiterating, although I'm tempted to increase 25-100k.

Whoa, the US is reporting ~1k cases today. That puts my current prediction at ~93k. My current model for cumulative cases isy_t = 9055*2^(t/16.1),with t = 0 on 7/8/22. This model predicts 20.5k cases by the end of today and 16.5k by last Friday, both of which were pretty accurate.So I'm going to put a little more weight on the 100k-250k bin for now, as it's possible that the forecast could end up pretty close to 100k.@Tolga @Dillyweed

To hit 25k cases, need 5700 cases in 33 days = 172 cases per day average. At current rate of 500/day would need to cut in half daily cases roughly every 7 days to have a chance of <25k. It's hard to see this happening, but part of me thinks it's still possible, only if there is a big turnaround this week. In principle I think halving time of new cases could be faster than the doubling time we saw during the initial stage of the outbreak
Prediction is now sub 100,000 based on doubling time

The numbers aren't growing fast enough anymore to have a reasonable chance of hitting 100k.I'm getting a little nervous about <25k, but with today's total probably ending up around 17k, it still doesn't look likely that will happen. ~3.7k added last week. I expect at least ~3k to be added this week, so that the total will be at least ~19.3k by the end of Friday. Then there will be ~4.5 weeks left to add <~5.7k cases. As long as there's not a major slowdown in cases, I think the result will be in bin 4.

According to my prophet model, (https://colab.research.google.com/drive/1I32v1tX4BHIkbO7JkQ0JKEu76PuVRRVp#scrollTo=eviq7GlbsvjA) both new cases-based and total cases-based method point to 35000+ cases.
It could get pretty close to the line between bins 4 and 5, and growth still seems exponential in at least some countries.
"95% Of Monkeypox Cases Transmitted Through Sexual Activity: Study"
At current doubling rates, it looks like 126k by August 31st, so a continued slowing, but seemingly a slowed slowing. Holding almost steady.
Confirmed cases already over 5,000 (~15,000) and spread already seems to be leveling off.

The doubling time has slowed to ~17 days (17.00 since 7/8), from ~12 (11.68 up to 7/8). This leads to a projection of 82k by Aug 31 -- without further slowing. Cases will likely ramp up disproportionately in the US as testing increases, but I don't think US cases are likely to be able to tip total cases over 100k at this point. And many countries with exponential growth in cases are testing only very small numbers of cases. So at this point, I don't think >100k is likely.

OWID shows that we haven't had a complete doubling in daily case numbers since June. It is very hard to imagine rapid doublings suddenly resuming. Maybe it could happen if monkeypox takes off in India, Russia, South America, etc - but what is testing capacity like there?

Using a very basic SIR model on the global numbers, curve fit with some bias toward more recent data, I'm getting ~200,000 by end of August. However, that comes out with an R0 of ~1.75, which I suspect is high, and it assumes no interventions beyond current ones, no changes of behavior, vaccination, etc. It also assumes there's no testing shortages or supply issues and backup there. Anecdotally on Reddit, people are already complaining of symptoms and being unable to meet testing criteria. So testing will lag cases a bit initially.

Needs *average* under 290 for the rest of the question period in order to hit sub 25k. After another 12 day so at ~500 daily cases, would need to average ~200 cases for the final month. This only really seems plausible to me if daily case numbers have already peaked and start going down quickly this week, which seems unlikely.

Growth has slowed in the Netherlands, too. At this point, with growth in cases slowing dramatically, I don't think 100k will be reached. It's possible that the 7-day average of cases/day could actually fall, too, to where <25k is possible.I was completely wrong in thinking cases would keep growing exponentially much longer.

Need to average >2000 per day for the rest of the question period in order to to hit 100k. At ~500/day now, is hard to see happening. Would need a bare minimum of three more doublings with a good amount of time left over.
Averaging a few of my guesses because I've already made 5 guesses today. Too much, @probahilliby. Hopefully it gives me confidence in my forecast and more importantly stability (the two are related).

Global cases are currently doubling every 14 days, which is slower than previously. It looks like early vaccination efforts in the UK have slowed the doubling rate from 12 to 24 days (!). We can expect to see continued slowing of doubling rates in the US and Europe, which is where the big outbreaks are centred currently. Many countries have stocks of smallpox vaccine so this is eminently containable worldwide.

The last month suggests about 0.0755 doublings per day, and we're 48 days (as of the last day of data) from August 31st, at 11,595, so that suggests about 143,000 cases as of August 31. To me, this suggests a fairly rapid decrease in doubling time, so I'm shifting lots of mass to the lower bucket.

Correcting an overly confident forecast (too much probability on extremely high case counts). But still cautious that fluctuations in reporting / detection could easily lead to an apparent slow-down that will actually not be sustained (counts will go up again shortly). I’ll sit tight and watch for a little while longer before adjusting further downwards, if current instantaneous trends continue.

Today's numbers aren't all in - we're still missing France and the US, among countries with the most cases - but it's clear that reported case growth has slowed from its previous exponential course. I did not expect to see this much slowing this early, but clearly I was wrong. I still expect large numbers of cases over the coming weeks and months, but it's starting to look to me like 25k-100k is most likely, but that even <25k might be possible. If there was this much slowing this week, then I think it's likely that we'll see more slowing in case growth next week and in the following weeks in many places that have seen the most cases so far.
I think the last bin is now out.
I think the numbers of reported cases are no longer growing fast enough for >250k to be plausible.

Germany apparently posted fewer cases this week than last. With some of the countries with the best testing also seeing limited growth (Portugal, UK, Germany), I think this makes the last bin increasingly less likely and bin 4 more plausible. I think I may have undervalued bin 4.
Growth appears to be slowing in England and Germany, for whatever reasons.

There are some signs of control in some of the W European countries with the biggest outbreaks, so I'm lowering my forecast on the last bin, at least for now. But, I'll see what tomorrow (Friday) brings, because Fridays are the best day of the week to assess case growth.
Was that like, 300+ cases just in Spain today?
Getting progressively closer to going all in on the exponential model being correct
My exponential model predicts 13.7k reported cases by the end of Friday. I'll expect this +/- 500 or so.

The increase in confirmed cased has been accelerating since the first confirmed case in May. From June to July, there was an increase of almost 8,000 confirmed cases. The increase will probably continue to accelerate.
Projecting forward based on doubling time for the past month puts us at about 200k. Could speed up or slow down - I see more margin for the latter than the former.
https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/jul/11/efforts-to-curb-uk-monkeypox-outbreak-inadequate-warn-experts-whistleblower-claim-helpline
https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/monkeypox-outbreak-technical-briefings/investigation-into-monkeypox-outbreak-in-england-technical-briefing-3
My theory is that testing is getting more efficient so detection is picking up. Objections?
On @belikewater ’s analysis. https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1477446
My guesses and hopes that the exponential tapers have so far been thwarted. Just no sign of that happening yet

Ok, my earlier comment today (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1477392 ) was premature. I had thought my model was predicting slightly too many cases for today, but it's not. The current total is 8939, with the US still to report, probably ~100 cases. So today's total will be ~9000. My exponential growth model, with a doubling time of 11.68 days, had predicted 8992 cases for today. So I think a doubling time of about 11.68 days is about right. So, I'm adjusting my forecast back up.I think we'll likely hit 25k in approx 2.5 weeks and 100k by sometime around 8/18, possibly substantially earlier or a bit later depending on what cases are doing in the US and elsewhere.As always, the question is when case growth will turn from exponential or nearly so. I think it will be quite a while to come before that happens.

I'm lowering my forecast on the last bin for now because today's numbers are slightly lower than expected. The current number is 8127, but the US can be expected to add ~100, and Spain hasn't reported; last Friday, Spain added 396 cases. Together, that would bring today's total to ~8625, but I would have expected 8992 for a doubling time of 11.68 days. It's still within the noise, but at least for now, I'll lower my forecast on the last bin. If today's total ends up at ~8625, that corresponds to a doubling time of almost exactly 12 days, which seems to be what the data keep bouncing around. That would put us at 197k by Aug 31. But again, US cases are likely to grow disproportionately, as testing becomes more available. For now, bin 5 looks most likely to me.
Huge jump in cases yesterday
July 27,2022 total outbreak == 19,188
Reverting back, I have a bad habit of overreacting to last week's data, which is pretty much always out of date.
7 day average has been flat for almost a week now... thought it was maybe 4th of July but the US added its most ever daily cases yesterday and that still wasn't enough.

If the growth rate remains the same it's currently on track for about 250,000 cases on the end date. I think the growth rate is more likely to decrease than increase, as I think there is a decent chance at some point in the next 1.5 months the WHO will declare a PHEIC and/or there will be a public health response to reduce the spread of the disease (so far, there has been almost no public health response of any note).
I am always right.

My exponential growth model with 2586 cases as of 6/17 and a doubling time of 11.68 days (doubling time from https://twitter.com/tjradcliffe/status/1541998012964057089 ) underestimates today's total, which is so far at 6106 without France or the US reporting. My model predicts 222k on 8/31. Of course, we don't know when case growth will slow from exponential, but I don't think it will slow much from exponential, if at all, by the end of August. Meanwhile, US testing will move from a 60/day capability to 10k/week starting in "early July." This could add a few thousand to the total, or 100k+. With all the sources of uncertainty (size of susceptible population, how much testing will increase in the US, how big the outbreak in the US really is, how much progress each country will make on controlling spread, etc.), I'm spreading my forecast nearly equally between the last 2 bins for now. I think <100k is extremely unlikely because I think the susceptible population is in the millions, and I don't see signs of control commensurate with what it would take to keep the total <100k.

Shifting upwards on bad news from the UK, Italy, Switzerland, and the US today. We're also seeing countries update their risk ratings upwards e.g., Switzerland moving it from low risk to moderate (https://twitter.com/Monkeypoxtally/status/1542891376387543042), so it's increasingly likely that we will see enough testing deployed to get into bins 5 and 6.
https://ourworldindata.org/monkeypox7 day average had its largest ever drop yesterday - likely noise

Current daily rate puts us at about 20k total cases, and daily rate is still going up globally. I still think containment is likely but at least during the question period it's going to look like a leveling off of new case growth rather than a total contraction, most likely

Looking at the data for Portugal, which was the basis for the hypothesis that Monkeypox could peak and be contained fairly quickly, it doesn't seem so clear-cut that this is the case right now. The US, which has a much greater population, seems to be going full steam ahead and as we saw with covid, might be more reluctant to put any mitigations in place - even testing is severely lacking for now https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2022/06/25/1107416457/monkeypox-outbreak-in-us?t=1656596018882.

I'm reducing the last bin but not because I'm eliminating it. I just think it's better to tighten it toward the consensus after realizing some of my calculations on the daily rates have resulted in less than 250k - less than 100k in fact. So based on these, I lower my possible overestimation on the later bins. Nonetheless, I'm still an astronomical distance from the 0% probability of the consensus - a jaw-dropping 15% difference.
4,992 today

It's really looking like cases are doubling around every 12 days. Exponential growth at that rate would put the total at just under 200k by the end of August. I think some slowing would put it a bit below that, firmly in bin 5. I would put a higher forecast on bin 5 for that reason except that US testing is just getting going. That could change everything and push the forecast into bin 6. So far, ~90% of cases are in W Europe, and <10% are in the US. But the US has over 1.5x the population of W Europe, so these numbers could change very quickly to more than twice what we're seeing now. And that would push the forecast well into bin 6. Now, we wait.
I'm increasingly reverting to my old theory that containment in some form occurs sooner rather than later

Portugal seems to be bringing their outbreak under control. It's not over, but it's not growing and is, if anything, shrinking. Canada may also be making similar progress. See the third graph below the map on the "MonkeyPox" tab here: https://www.ilpandacentrostudio.it/uk.html
Hedging a bit as I feel it might have been a bit early to entirely discard bin 3 before it was even reached.
Current best estimate: 141k. Control efforts will pull that down a bit, and increased testing in the US will push it up.
Model still fits quadratic growth pretty well! Actually much better now - R2 = 99%. I'll stick with this model.

https://twitter.com/UpupaEp55949188/status/1541214324710166528https://ourworldindata.org/explorers/monkeypox?facet=none&hideControls=false&Metric=Confirmed+cases&Frequency=7-day+average&Shown+by=Date+of+confirmation&country=PRT~ESPIt is looking like, possibly, Portugal has had the worst outbreak per capita, and has also, possibly maybe, got case growth under control.Portugal has 350 total cases and a population of 10 million. If you ballpark it at 600m people in countries with decent detection systems and active outbreaks, then this translates to somewhere in the 20,000s before cases flare out globally. I shouldn't want to update too quickly on this yet, but I am adjusting down my numbers a good bit. It is consistent with the theory that I had held up until the last week, that cases would level off relatively quickly since this is what happens in most disease outbreaks, and cases are still relegated to MSM which means the total # of susceptible people is quite low, like 1% of the population or less.
@Tolga @belikewater
Moving to 50:50 as it seems the doubling rate is currently about every 10 days, putting us right on the line. I'll model later.

Portugal seems to be getting the outbreak there under control! That is very impressive. And growth may be slowing a bit in some other countries (but by no means all). So I will weight bin 3 a bit higher and add a few % to bin 2, just in case. Not enough is happening in most places, though, including the US, which will soon ramp up testing. It's hard to say, but the last bin may be looking slightly less likely now. If cases double every 14 days and exponential growth continues throughout the forecast period (and it won't be exactly exponential, as some countries continue to dampen the outbreak, others don't, and fractions tested change), then the total on Aug. 31 would be 107k, just over 100k. With testing ramping up in the US, though, the total could end up anywhere.
Hedging a bit higher on bin 4, just in case. I see the consensus is about to flip from bin 3 to bin 4.

Cases going up by almost 250 per day now. @belikewater pointed out that my math was crap and so I now have it at about 50/50 of hitting 100k based purely on the exponential, and am keeping more % in lower buckets to account for the possibility of both testing constraints artificially suppressing counts, and the outbreak just flaring out.
Seems like the “limited spread in MSM party scene” scenario is exceedingly unlikely to be the main part of this story going forward, to state the obvious.

Looking like doubling time in daily cases is close to 2 weeks based on https://ourworldindata.org/monkeypox. That's the simplest model and it results in about 70k cases by my count. I also think as cases go up, you are more likely to miss cases due to low testing capacity. Leaving 14% each for a high or low error bar, i.e. below <25k or >100k total cases. Leaving another 6% for containment, i.e. <25k. Curve looks exponential right now but could end up being logistic instead if cases are just burning through a relatively small networks of highly promiscuous people, or something like that, but it's seeming increasingly unlikely.

Repeating my forecast and tweaking my model some more. The total is at 3761 right now, and cases for England, Madrid (Spain) and France haven't even been reported yet. Last Friday, those countries reported 288 cases on Friday, and that was before England moved to reporting cases only twice a week. So with case growth, I think we can expect several hundred more to be reported today. So, for now, here's a new model, which is just slightly different from my old model - still exponential growth, with a more careful initial case count and date:

I'm now forecasting more than 100,000 plus or minus with a tail end for an underestimation of how much higher than we expect this to go, but then adjusted a little bit to lean on current consensus. I did not factor in any potential ceilings. Purely based on assumption that the trend continues.

My current exponential growth model for cumulative cases:y_t = 2550 * 2^(t/10), where y_t = cumulative cases on day t, and t=0 on 6/18/22This model predicts 3865 cases by the end of Friday, >5k on 6/28, >25k on 7/21, >100k on 8/10, >250k on 8/24. Given that Thursday's total is already at 3422 and that ~460 cases were reported last Friday, this model likely slightly underestimates actual reported cases.
Just repeating my forecast to share an exponential fit with a doubling time for cumulative cases of 9 days:https://twitter.com/JamesHebda/status/1539680656665485312

I'm quite cautious to cling on to the higher bins because the crowd median is still quite high in bin 3, at 82%. GJO tells us the participants on this question comprising the crowd median is "better than average." So there's that. However, I still expect the consensus to shift to those later bins as @belikewater has shifted to early on in his forecasts. And he has the data to back it up. It seems the shift is beginning to occur with other forecasters with their own models as well. It sure is shifting in my day-to-day understanding.

Going for a fairly evenly split on the last three bins. Now that Monkeypox is in the US and that the US will start testing more seriously as @belikewater found, I'm definitely expecting many more cases to start showing up, but I'm also leaving room for mitigations to be put in place in the short to medium term (with respect to the question's timeline) that might keep things in bin 4.
I'm starting to think "More than 100,000 but fewer than 250,000" is the increasingly more likely option. But obviously I remain unsure probabilistically.
My monkey brain sees that the exponential trend seems to be getting underway. Where is the ceiling?

An approx. 10-day doubling rate for cumulative cases is looking increasingly reasonable. It took ~10 days for cases to go from 1k to 2k and ~11 days to go from 1.5k to 3k, with noisy data. 2k cases were reached on June 15, so I'll expect to see ~4k cases by ~June 25. As of right now, June 22, there are 3315 cases, with 158 reported today, so with Friday's UK and Madrid cases, in addition to cases from everywhere else, it seems likely that we'll see ~700 more cases in the next 3 days - although June 25 is a Saturday, so we might not actually cross 4k until this coming Monday. Last Friday saw 460 cases, though, so chances are, we'll cross 4k on Friday.
Updating.
I'm gradually passing from denial into acceptance on this one I think
Daily rate has us on target for 15k. If daily rate goes up even by 1.5x then we likely hit >25k. Has to go up quite a bit faster than I'm seeing in order for us to break 100k though.
increasing my uncertainty a little bit to be safe

Current daily rate puts us at about ~15k by end of the question period. Daily rate has been going up, contra my hopes and initial expectations. If doubling time of daily cases is about two weeks I think we end up with maybe 70k cases by the end of the question period, but my error bars on that still skew to the lower end, because most outbreaks like this level off rather than continuing. 250k remains totally impossible as long as r0 remains within bounds that seem plausible, and cases relegated to adult males
Repeating my forecast to say that by the end of Tuesday, I expect to see somewhere in the ballpark of 3500 total cases. And >=~4400 by the end of Friday.
Shifting my prediction a lot after not paying much attention for a while and now catching up on the discussion between @belikewater @Dillyweed @JPH.

I'm seeing more tweets like this one, about a potential monkeypox case in an adult and toddler in San Francisco, non-sexual transmission: "Public health refusing to give me and my 2 y/o #Monkeypox testing. Flu like symptoms and now covered in small pustules. Differentials have been ruled out. Strict criteria for testing will lead to uncontrollable spread like COVID19.@UCSFHospitals @DanielGriffinMD @CAPublicHealth"https://twitter.com/longestrecovery/status/1534343073060098049
Looking at the actual base rate of infections the range between 5000 and 25000 is the most probable scenario.
Updating based on recent case counts. My view is this is high R0 (~1.5-2) in a small demographic (~40-60k: 1% of sexually active MSM with highest number of sexual partners/month).
The only way I think cases could end up <100k at this point is if countries saturate testing capabilities or just stop testing any but the most severe cases.
Thank you, this is extremely helpful. It seems I should take some time to read and understand this paper more carefully.
Update later in the day: the total is now 2504.
(This was a mistake. Updated above.)
Going to flatten my curve if you'll pardon the expression, just to be safe
It is not spreading as exponentially as other deseases.
Cases still seem to be almost entirely adult males

My toy model of exponential growth predicts 2067 cumulative cases by the end of June 16, according to the source data Google sheet, and we're already at 2066. (I guess we technically have to subtract 5 from Ghana, so 2061.) So I think this model likely is currently very slightly under-predicting cases. It predicts 86.1k cumulative cases by the end of Aug. 31, but I think it's quite possible that we could see >100k cumulative cases by the end of August.
Cases not slowing down like had hoped. <5k no longer very viable

Uh-oh. Many people are getting a rash in the mouth. I was wondering how common this was. This will lead to airborne transmission like a respiratory virus. It probably won't be too important for this question, but watch out this fall and winter.

I think some of my early forecasts on this question were too optimistic, based on the possibility that if most reported cases were transmitted among MSM, then it would be easier to control and there would be a big effort to control it. But we've known for at least a couple weeks now that cases among MSM aren't being controlled sufficiently. And we see exponential growth in cases. It's slow, but it's exponential. It's possible that a larger-scale effort will be made to control spread in the near future, but on the course we're on now, I think we need to expect exponential growth. My toy model projects we'll see 86k cases by Aug 31. It could easily be off in either direction, but it strongly suggests that bin 4 is very likely. But, it's only 4 days of cases short of passing 100k, so I think bin 5 should be given a substantial chance, too. Here are my model's projections: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1467761
Daily cases, based on the source-associated spreadsheet:
1806 cases today. This is an increase of 334 cases 4 days, or 83 cases per day.

My simple exponential model is, sadly, not doing too badly so far. As before, the equation I'm using right now for daily cases, based on the source-associated spreadsheet, isy_t = 64*2^(t/15), where t = 0 on 6/3/22, and cumulative cases at t=0 is 900.This model predicts 1950 cumulative cases by the end of June 15. The data are noisy, but as of right now, the total on the source-associated spreadsheet is 1988. (The map says 1806 and needs to be updated.)
[Forgot to update foreacst.]

I feel I'm underestimating 1,000 to 5,000.* My calculations have hovered around 5,000 plus or minus. On the other hand, though, my mental model is poor and underinformed, so I won't give my analyses much credence.
Reversing my previous forecast. The number of cases per day is relatively high and the trend looks like it's gonna end in the third bin.

The source data group has now added a few things:Data viz page: https://www.monkeypox.global.health/Github: https://github.com/globaldothealth/monkeypoxFound information here: https://twitter.com/MOUGK/status/1536329223899688961
Down a bit on Bin 3 in favour of Bin 2, cases are growing steadily but not accelerating to the extent that they could stall if greater awareness and preventive measures were put in place.
Pushing points to last bin in case of exponential trend. Unsure if this will level out so I'm debating whether or not to put more points into bin 2 (Between 1,000 and 1,500, inclusive).

“Explosive” growth in cases leading to the higher bin outcomes looks exceedingly unlikely, given the amount of time that has passed and the fact that large changes in the infection rate haven’t been observed in the meantime.

Judging by Our World In Data, last week we had 551 new cases, week before was 522. This is remarkably flat, and while I can't rule out a coming exponential takeoff (keeping in mind all of the ~2 week period between infection and a positive test and many other random factors, variation in testing, etc), containment seems plausible as long as new cases are a slow burn. If new cases continue at roughly the current rate we should be at around 7000 cases by the end of the question period.
1472 cases reported. Small number of suspected cases.
I think I really have been too low on bin 4 out of wishful thinking.

I've had a low forecast on bin 4 (25k-100k) because of uncertainty around monkeypox detection, spread, and control and because of hopefulness that cases won't grow quickly. Given monkeypox's long incubation period and hence generation time, it is too early to distinguish conclusively between several models. But it feels like wishful thinking not to assign more weight to an exponential model, when I don't see any reason to rule it out at this point. My exponential model would put reported cases toward the upper end of bin 4, so I'm increasing my forecast on bin 4. Even if spread is largely constrained within the MSM community throughout the forecast period, that community, while very heterogeneous, is also very large.
Calculation error for bin B. Fixing.

In case it's useful to anyone, the equation I'm using right now for daily cases isy_t = 64*2^(t/15), where t = 0 on 6/3/22, and cumulative cases at t=0 is 900.It's a rough estimate that will need to be adjusted with additional data and changing circumstances, of course. It would put us at ~5k cumulative cases by early July. It's an underestimate already, though, because it has been on target the past couple days without any reporting from England since Tuesday (i.e., nothing for Wed or Thurs yet), when their mandatory reporting rule went into effect.

Up date today over 1,000 cases reported today.
Can't be lower than 1K right now

theres no validated test for monkey pox and the therefore global health will not report anything most likely mainly because they don’t want to be investigated by Interpol and others because their organization most likely relies on public funds for operations but there could be a nefarious actor within their organization that knows this and plans on using mind readers and fake data to publish information just my thoughts
It is already over 1000. So 0 the below 1000 branch.
Concentrating my forecast more on lower bins now because people are not identifying a wider swath of patients at this time.

Case numbers running between 900 and 1000 now. There are also a small number of suspected cases. So it looks to be slowing down a bit. Bin 1 is out, most likely bin 2, with small possibility of bin 3.
Only way to spread is close personal contact!
Big revision to previous forecast based on extrapolation of case counts over time.

Don't have time to make a full rationale, but I recommend everyone reads @belikewater's rationales [1]. Summary of my view is that it's not clear how quickly it's currently growing but looks like at the moment it's doubling every 5-7 days. I agree with @Dillyweed's rationale [2] saying that the current rate of growth will probably decrease over the medium term.
